California, with senior rights to the Colorado River, would face cuts last, impacting Arizona, Nevada, and Mexico first.
The river system, supplying water to millions, is drier and more prone to drought.
Agricultural water is crucial for urban use in the arid U.S. Water wars loom as temperatures rise and flows decrease.
Drought has left reservoirs half empty, prompting water reallocation.
Climate change exacerbates the situation, with predictions of reduced flows.
The Southwest faces a Dust Bowl-like dry spell, leading to water scarcity and potential conflicts over allocation.
